<DOC><DOCNO> AP890313-0087 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-13-89 1326EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Malawi-Floods     03-13 0136</FIRST><SECOND>AM-BRF--Malawi-Floods,0141</SECOND><HEAD>Floods Kill Six, Leave 37,000 Homeless</HEAD><DATELINE>BLANTYRE, Malawi (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Torrential rain and floods in southernMalawi killed six people and left 37,000 homeless, officials saidMonday.   Floodwaters that swept away mud huts and prefabricated sheltersin Chikwawa and Nsanje districts drowned the six victims, includingtwo children, local administrators said.   About 20,000 people are homeless in Nsanje, near the southeasternborder with Mozambique, according to a government administrator.   Red Cross officials said 17,000 other homeless are receivingfood, blankets and tents at Chikwawa, about 70 miles south ofBlantyre.   Some displaced families are being sheltered in schools, churches,government and other brick buildings that withstood the flooding,they said.   Travelers arriving in Blantyre told of entire villages beingdestroyed and widespread damage to corn crops in the worst floodsrecorded since 1956.</TEXT></DOC>